@flexiarg structure/interest-event-vocabulary
@title What state-transition is this checkpoint asserting against an interest-network entity?
@sigils [⌒/態]
@keywords vocabulary, state-transition, checkpoint, interest-network, posterior-update, EoI, event-log, append-only, provenance, state-spawned, state-refined, state-strengthened, state-addressed, state-falsified, state-foreclosed, state-reopened, link-asserted
@audience operators authoring mission checkpoints that need to update the standing of EoI entities; engine code that emits state-transition events; projection code that derives posterior state from the event log; downstream consumers (substrate-2 sorry-typing, M-a-sorry-enterprise mining-track, :sorry/r3d-per-entity-attribution) that need a shared entity-status vocabulary
@tone declarative; vocabulary first
@factor Investigation (dhammavicaya)
@references [structure/unresolved-tensions-at-closure structure/whose-question-is-this writing-coherence/name-what-you-drop]
@references-extra ["Mission of origin: ~/code/futon4/holes/missions/M-interest-network-coupling.md (§2.0 checkpoint metadata, §2.1 event vocabulary, §2.2 emission format, §3 ARGUE)" "Sibling prior-art for vocabulary-as-EDN (shape reference; not directly composed): ~/code/futon5a/data/war-machine-strategic-vocabulary.edn + war-machine-terminal-vocabulary.edn" "Corpus the vocabulary operates over: ~/code/atthangika-buckets.json eoi_instances[] + institution_objects[]" "Cross-mission consumers identified in claude-1 downstream finding 2026-05-26: M-action-cost-modelling §3.2 (geometry-track sorry-typing in substrate-2), M-a-sorry-enterprise (mining-track), :sorry/r3d-per-entity-attribution (futon2/data/sorrys.edn)"]

! conclusion:
  Mission checkpoints update the interest-network not by mutating EoI
  entities directly but by emitting typed state-transition events
  that target them. This flexiarg declares the v1 vocabulary: eight
  event types (seven `state/*` events plus `link/asserted`) and a
  payload schema. The event log is append-only and
  provenance-bearing; the posterior projection derives entity
  standing by replay. The vocabulary is neutral — the same eight
  events apply to essay annotations, institution-objects, basins,
  and composite-arrow edges without entity-class-specific slang.

  + context: The EoI corpus declares interests as a prior. Lived
    evidence from missions (M-interim-director during design
    2026-05-14 → ~2026-05-28; downstream validation execution
    ~June–August 2026; EoI engine runs in any session) constitutes
    the likelihood. The interest-network surface renders the
    posterior. Without an explicit event vocabulary, mission outputs
    sit alongside the EoI corpus as parallel documents rather than
    as posterior updates; the network either ossifies (silent
    updates) or churns incoherently (overwrites without provenance).
    The vocabulary closes this gap by giving every state-transition
    a citable name.

  + HOWEVER: Three design choices the vocabulary makes, and why each
    beats its alternative.

    + EIGHT-EVENTS-NOT-FREE-FORM:
      A free-form rationale field per checkpoint would be simpler
      but loses the structure that lets the projection compute
      coverage, detect inconsistencies, and render the network
      without re-parsing prose. Eight types is enough to
      discriminate (a) entity-lifecycle moves (spawned / refined /
      strengthened) from (b) closure moves (addressed / falsified /
      foreclosed / reopened) from (c) relational moves
      (link/asserted), while staying small enough that an operator
      can hold them in mind without consulting a sheet.

    + STATE-SLASH-PREFIX-NEUTRAL:
      Namespace is `state/*` — not `eoi/*`, `essay/*`, `basin/*` —
      so the same events apply to essay annotations,
      institution-objects, basins, and composite-arrow edges.
      Granularity is a separate field (`:target/granularity`), not
      part of the event-type. Cross-entity-class queries work
      naturally ("show me every entity that got addressed this
      week"); per-entity-class queries filter by granularity.

    + LINK-AS-SEPARATE-EVENT:
      `link/asserted` is its own event type, not a special case of
      `state/spawned`, because "new relation exists" and "new entity
      exists" have different downstream uses (relation surfaces as
      edge in the network view; entity surfaces as node).
      Overloading `state/spawned` would force the projection to
      discriminate by `:target/granularity` to know whether to
      render as node or edge — fine for the projection, opaque to
      the operator authoring the checkpoint.

  + THEN: The eight event types, the payload schema, and the
    emission discipline.

    + EVENT-VOCABULARY-V1:
      - `state/spawned`     — Target entity is newly created.
      - `state/refined`     — Target entity's framing has been
        sharpened (re-anchor, scoped).
      - `state/strengthened` — Target entity's standing has gained
        support from evidence.
      - `state/addressed`   — Target entity (typically a tension)
        has been resolved by evidence; not falsified.
      - `state/falsified`   — Target entity has been contradicted by
        evidence.
      - `state/foreclosed`  — Target entity (typically a basin) has
        been deliberately closed off.
      - `state/reopened`    — Target entity that was
        addressed/falsified/foreclosed has had its standing reset
        to `:live`. First-class so retraction isn't terminal.
      - `link/asserted`     — A new cross-essay relation exists.
        Separate from `state/spawned` to avoid overloading "new
        target" with "new relation".

    + PAYLOAD-SCHEMA:
      Each event record carries these fields (EDN, keyword keys):
      - `:event/id`           — unique within checkpoint
      - `:event/type`         — keyword; one of the eight above
      - `:checkpoint/ref`     — back-pointer to the checkpoint
      - `:target/entity-id`   — the EoI entity this event targets
      - `:target/granularity` — keyword; one of `:essay`, `:section`,
        `:annotation`, `:institution-object`, `:basin`,
        `:composite-arrow`
      - `:prior-state`        — keyword; standing before this event.
        Required for `state/*` events; optional/omitted for
        `link/asserted`.
      - `:posterior-state`    — keyword; standing after this event.
        Required for `state/*` events; optional/omitted for
        `link/asserted`.
      - `:evidence/refs`      — `[String]`; pointers to evidence
        artefacts (interview notes, go/nogo memos, plan drafts,
        EoI strawman sections, etc.)
      - `:operator/rationale` — `String`; the operator's
        plain-language reason. This is the load-bearing
        provenance field; the projection's posterior always
        traces back to an operator-asserted *because*.
      - `:link/src`           — `String`; source entity. Only for
        `link/asserted` events.
      - `:link/dst`           — `String`; destination entity. Only
        for `link/asserted` events.

    + EMISSION-DISCIPLINE:
      - APPEND-ONLY. Events are never edited or deleted. Mistakes
        are corrected by emitting a new event (typically
        `state/refined` or `state/reopened`) that updates the
        target's standing. The log is the authoritative source;
        the projection derives current state from log replay.
      - NO-OP DAYS EMIT NO CHECKPOINT. Daily cadence is fine when
        there's a real state delta — even a single `state/refined`
        on a single annotation counts. But synthetic checkpoints
        (an empty `:emitted-events` vector emitted just to satisfy
        a daily rhythm) are forbidden: they pollute the log with
        non-events and degrade the projection's signal-to-noise.
      - OPERATOR-ASSERTED BOUNDARY. Events are emitted at
        checkpoint boundaries by an operator, not inferred from
        prose by a processor. The event log is authored, not
        extracted. (Pre-checkpoint events — interview notes, go/nogo
        memos as they happen — are out of scope for v1.)
      - VALIDATION BLOCKS, NOT WARNS. Validation errors against
        this vocabulary block the checkpoint; the operator fixes
        the EDN and re-runs. Silent acceptance of malformed events
        would let drift land in the projection.

  + BECAUSE:
    Provenance is the load-bearing part of completeness-not-closure
    (the parent EoI mission's framing: the network becomes more
    complete under use because evidence accumulates, not because
    documents multiply). The projection's render answers "what is
    the standing of every EoI entity right now?", but the trail it
    carries answers "how did it get there?". Both are needed:
    without standing, the operator can't act on current state;
    without trail, the operator can't tell whether progress is real
    or a confabulation. The eight-event vocabulary fixes a
    discrimination-shape the projection can compute against; the
    append-only discipline preserves the trail; the
    explicit-emission rule keeps the authoring surface honest. The
    neutral `state/*` namespace makes the vocabulary reusable
    across entity classes — which is what lets substrate-2's
    sorry-typing, M-a-sorry-enterprise's mining-track, and
    `:sorry/r3d-per-entity-attribution` adopt the same vocabulary
    rather than re-inventing it per consumer.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
